    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-13T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-13T12:00:00-05:00" n="470"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d470">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.85/14</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-13T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 13, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.27 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>10034. War Trade Board [from <persName corresp="#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName>]:</p>
                <p>575. The following names of Russian steamers requisitioned by the British. His
                    Majesty’s Government only regard principle of 50 per cent division between
                    British and United States Governments as applying to neutral and ex-enemy
                    tonnage, and had not considered this as applying to Russian ships. They are
                    willing, however, to agree to 50 per cent division of those ships which were not
                    previously engaged in European-Allied service prior to November 24, 1917, this
                    reservation being the same as that made by the United States Government in
                    respect to the Norwegian vessels. His Majesty’s Government state that they
                    expect the United States Government to apply same principle of division to any
                    Japanese ships that may be acquired by negotiation.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                    <item>In European-Allied service previously, steamers <hi rend="italic"
                            >Ekaterinoslav</hi>, gross tons 6,581, <hi rend="italic">Tambov</hi>
                        4,441, <hi rend="italic">Yaroslavl</hi> 4,495, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Novgorod</hi> 5,285, <hi rend="italic">Voronej</hi> 5,616, <hi
                            rend="italic">Mogilev</hi> 6,377, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Kamenetz-Podolsk</hi> 5,071, <hi rend="italic">Vologda</hi> 4,784, <hi
                            rend="italic">Krasnoiarsk</hi> 5,812, <hi rend="italic">Ellind</hi>
                        2,826, <hi rend="italic">Soroka</hi> 1,630, <hi rend="italic">Odessa</hi>
                        1,679, <hi rend="italic">Umba</hi> 2,042, <hi rend="italic">Claudius
                            Aulagnon</hi> 3,967, <hi rend="italic">Sibir</hi> 2,907, <hi
                            rend="italic">Ibis</hi> 2,358, <hi rend="italic">Altai</hi>
                        <pb facs="0363" n="313" xml:id="pg_313"/> 3,756, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Biruta</hi> 1,732, <hi rend="italic">Graf Stroganoff</hi> 2,911, <hi
                            rend="italic">Zimorodok</hi> 3,578, <hi rend="italic">Kurland</hi> 896,
                            <hi rend="italic">Marie Rose</hi> 3,023, <hi rend="italic">Bjarmia</hi>
                        1,386, <hi rend="italic">Trio</hi> 678, <hi rend="italic">Constantia</hi>
                        772, <hi rend="italic">Sirius</hi> 1,004, <hi rend="italic">Agnes</hi> 877,
                            <hi rend="italic">Leda</hi> 1,208, <hi rend="italic">Sicilia</hi> 1,794,
                            <hi rend="italic">Alexa</hi> 605, <hi rend="italic">Czar</hi> 6,516, <hi
                            rend="italic">Czaritza</hi> 6,598, <hi rend="italic">Dwinsk</hi> 8,173,
                            <hi rend="italic">Kursk</hi> 7,869, <hi rend="italic">Kaite</hi> 2,423,
                            <hi rend="italic">Ethelaida</hi> 2,669, <hi rend="italic">Vitim</hi>
                        unknown.</item>
                    <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                    <item>Not in European-Allied service previously, owners eastern trade, <persName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Edward Bary</hi>
                        </persName> 1,794, <hi rend="italic">Ivan Azbeteff</hi> 1,801, <hi
                            rend="italic">Ural</hi> 2,063, <hi rend="italic">Baikal</hi> 2,269, <hi
                            rend="italic">Eugenia</hi> 2,079, <hi rend="italic">Indighirka</hi>
                        2,336, <hi rend="italic">Tobolsk</hi> 2,693.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
